metadata.name: Waxing Crescent #70
metadata.description:
A generator for the mascot of darkness.

The moons are generated with a real-time GAN of 1.6M parameters that has been trained on thousands of photos collected on the internet.

metadata.name: Stitched: Trauma #481
metadata.description:
"Every happy family is alike; every unhappy family is unhappy in its own way." -- Tolstoy

Stitched: trauma is based on the same code, and premise, as Stitched, with one twist: childhood trauma distorts experiences and events; some are wildly chaotic; others obsessively retrace a few curves. It is an experiment in combinatorial complexity: are two mints ever indistinguishable? 

The distortion has been carefully designed to allow a huge space of legibly distinct possibilities.

controls:

mouse click or space bar: pause / unpause / reset animation
s: save current frame
f: toggle between square format and stretch aspect ratio
1-6: set pixel density

attributes.name: Symmetry
attributes.value: Reflection in x, Reflection across x-y=0

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #231
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #119
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: Trust #289
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or  ‘3’ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)
Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle brush texture

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Tangentum #44
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Tally! #8307
metadata.description:
Tally! Is a year long, free, open edition to celebrate fxhash v2. Data from the minting of Tally! will be used to create other new artworks.

This artwork is simply about counting up from one to wherever we end up, with a litle bit of Fizz Buzz thrown in. Mints that have a prime numbers* as factors will have slight variations. Sometimes those variations will combine, sometimes you have to get to really high numbers for multiple prime numbers to combine.

Where the finally Tally! ends up who knows? But there's going to be a lot of tallying along the way, and it'll give you something to do while waiting between other mints.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

'?forceWidth=xxxx' on the end of the URL to change the width of the image
's' = save image

metadata.name: Timing #355
metadata.description:
Time.. 
While one thing happens one time, another happens several times.

----------------------------------------------------------------
  Keys control:
    r: toggle rotation
    i: increment rotation speed
    d: decrement rotation speed
    p: toggle show points
    s: save current size image to .png
    x + 2/4/8: save 2x/4x/8x size image to .png
    1-9 + g: save 1-9 sec animation to .gif (depends on the machine resources)

  URL parameters:
    fps=<value>: frame rate
    r=true: rotation ON
    p=false: do not show points
